{
  "doc_id": "22107",
  "text": "Extracellular RNA has become a focus for developing new diagnostic strategies for identifying disease or abnormal pathologies [CITATION_1] . Studies have shown that a class of small RNA, microRNAs (miRNAs), are secreted from tumor cells into the blood of patients and can be used to diagnose cancer with high specificity [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . miRNAs are relatively stable in the extracellular environment as they are either bound to proteins such as Argonaute 2 (Ago2) or are contained within exosomes (Valadi et al., 2007; [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Likewise, mRNAs are packaged into exosomes and secreted by cells into the extracellular environment (Valadi et al., 2007) . Neither the mechanism for selection of which RNAs are secreted, nor are the roles of extracellular miRNA and mRNA well understood. However, extracellular RNA may play a role in cell-cell communication (Valadi et al., 2007) . While the function of extracellular RNA is largely unknown, the high stability and selective secretion into the environment allows for the potential to use these RNAs as biomarkers.",
